  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "The evolution of anti-money laundering (AML) legislation has been significant:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970, US)\n- First international recognition of money laundering as a criminal activity\n- Initial focus on financial reporting requirements\n\n2. Key Milestones\n- FATF establishment (1989)\n- UN Convention against Illicit Drugs (1988)\n- Patriot Act (2001) - Expanded AML regulations post-9/11\n\n3. Modern Developments\n- Enhanced customer due diligence requirements\n- Stricter reporting standards\n- Increased international cooperation\n- Broader definition of financial crimes\n\n4. Technological Adaptations\n- Regulations addressing cryptocurrency\n- Enhanced digital transaction monitoring\n- Machine learning and AI in detecting suspicious activities\n\n5. Recent Trends\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n- Greater transparency requirements\n- Expanded scope to include beneficial ownership\n- Cross-border information sharing mechanisms\n\n6. Current Focus Areas\n- Combating terrorist financing\n- Preventing cryptocurrency-related money laundering\n- Addressing complex digital financial transactions\n\nThese legislative developments reflect ongoing efforts to create more comprehensive and adaptive frameworks against financial crimes.",
